is, "What's next?" One possibility is sort of it's the end of this cycle, i=
t's a mature industry now. If you look at other industries, electricity and=
 cars and other things, there was a period of rapid change and then at some=
 point they stabilize. That's one hypothesis. I don't believe that, but tha=
t's one view you could have=E2=80=A6
I believe, personally, that the most exciting new computing wave is blockch=
ains and crypto.
Thompson=E2=80=99s confidence in the incumbents was based on the idea that =
even if new input/output (I/O) devices like wearables, voice, or AR replace=
s the phone, the incumbents are still in the best position to capture the o=
pportunity. Facebook doesn=E2=80=99t care if you scroll the feed on your ph=
one, AR glasses, or VR goggles -- it will serve you its feed, and the ads t=
hat support it, anywhere, anytime. It might even sell you the devices. The =
front-end is relatively meaningless; the incumbents are still best-position=
ed on the back-end.=C2=A0
But Thompson missed Web3 in his list of potential threats, and Web3 changes=
 some important things that the incumbents are not best-positioned to handl=
e.=C2=A0
To start, blockchains are not just a new I/O device. They aren=E2=80=99t de=
vices at all. They represent a new paradigm.
Blockchains and crypto let you do things that previous computing paradigms =
couldn=E2=80=99t, the most important of which, according to Dixon, is that =
you can =E2=80=9Cwrite code that makes strong commitments about how it will=
 behave in the future.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
No one person or company can change the rules. There will only ever be 21 m=
illion bitcoin, no matter what anyone tries to do to change that. Strong co=
mmitments extend far beyond bitcoin, to Non-Fungible Tokens (NFTs), Decentr=
alized Finance (DeFi), Decentralized Autonomous Organizations (DAOs), and n=
ew blockchain-based products no one=E2=80=99s yet dreamed up.=C2=A0
If the code can make strong commitments, you don=E2=80=99t need central pla=
tforms to make and enforce the rules. They just create economic drag. Inste=
ad, you can allow creators and consumers to share more of the profits that =
Aggregators and Platforms previously captured.=C2=A0
Blockchains can make commitments to developers, too. Unlike Apple=E2=80=99s=
 App Store, or Facebook, or Twitter, the rules are known from the start and=
 they don=E2=80=99t change when a company decides it needs to increase prof=
its. If you=E2=80=99re building a new app on top of the Ethereum or Solana =
[https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEGOhCAQRU_TLA0gqCxYzGauYUqq2iaNYABn4=
u2H1sUkBFL8VP36z0GlNeXT7qlU9rnmeu5kI_2WQLVSZkehPHu0YpBTr5VhaBWKSU_Ml_mZiTbw=
wdZ8ENuPJXgH1ad4dXAuNXtZNxjOgS-TVnqUGuXTaHTKjDgigpxuXzjQU3Rk6YfymSKxYF-17uX=
Rfz3kdzslBYjQubS1gnkruRRcyUH0nGveia7XfHBGC4MLoBADSIEwNtORFhoJH4pvq-zKsZQK7v=
2ZxLKNqS4p-7g2-f2CjcIltDBze7cj-nrOFGEJhHfOeuO6ks8rRcoNI85QGyRhlJK8cdL8ztVA9=
Lp9tzVZc8bUuuK_6R_7ZoAq] blockchains, you know what you=E2=80=99re getting.=
 You can plug into a growing number of superpowers with confidence that the=
y=E2=80=99ll always be there, even if the people behind them go away.
That changes everything.=C2=A0
Disrupting the Undisruptable
Disruption comes in two forms.=C2=A0
Low-End Disruption: Serving consumers who are overserved by incumbents, typ=
ically at a lower price point with a =E2=80=9Cgood enough=E2=80=9D product.
New-Market Disruption: Creating a market where none existed by turning non-=
consumers into consumers.=C2=A0
Traditionally, disrupters observe the state of the market, identify overser=
ved or unserved consumers, and jump in to steal demand the incumbents don=
=E2=80=99t want. Remember, though, that the Aggregators want all of the dem=
and. They want to serve everyone well, at the lowest possible cost. They ha=
ven=E2=80=99t left an opening.=C2=A0
Sometimes, though, a new technology creates an opening where none existed.=
=C2=A0
In a 2016 HBR piece, What Would it Take to Disrupt a Platform Like Facebook=
? [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkU2OwyAMhU9TdomAQH4WLGYz14hMcBNUAhF=
xpurtx9MuRkK24enpWR8LEK6lvtxRThJ_ZabXgS7j80xIhFVcJ9Y5Bqd6PXbWTCI4E9RoRxHP-V=
4Rd4jJUb1QHJdPcQGKJb8dUmorNtcbtfhumAxfO6V7BJAmWAAVxj5M4ycXrhAxL-jwB-urZBTJb=
UTHeeu-bvqbz-ZrW-rKk5aq5yY7Ls8NqHmWK4UmUkPwwIZKE-JZr4MaaI4EdC91b1Jk6Q4L-lIe=
IjottZJG96qT0spWtZ2V_TJZNQUPQaketAowGDsM6HHAcDNyX3V7Xv4kWB7tUnZRXS7kS415Zfm=
xwY7pLTCLmft-5UivGTP4hOGDiT603-DmFTNW_oUwAzFjNRmjJWO28oOFOXaWn3lNwcmhsCv_h_=
4ChV6VnA], Joshua Gans wrote:
Supply-side disruption arises when a new innovation or technology offers a =
better way of providing consumer value than the old technology does...
Blockchains and crypto are the new technology that offers a better way of p=
roviding consumer value than the old technology does. It=E2=80=99s the comp=
uting shift that Thompson missed and Dixon picked up on. Blockchains aren=
=E2=80=99t a new I/O device, they=E2=80=99re a fundamentally new back-end o=
n top of which =E2=80=9Ca smaller company with fewer resources=E2=80=9D can=
 build products that scale and evolve rapidly.=C2=A0
Blockchains and the ecosystems on top of them allow entrepreneurs to build =
huge projects with very lean teams. It comes down to scalability and compos=
ability.=C2=A0
My friend Jon Wu [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uwyAQhU8TlhZgwPaC=
RTe9BuJn4tDYYMHQyLcviReV0CBm9HjzPm8R1lxOfeSK5F0MngfoBK-6ASIU0ioUE4Nmis-jFAs=
JWgQ2y5nEau4FYLdx01gakKO5LXqLMaePglIuyUNPdxqcFIqqyYIN8-LvXT6PavZ0EcpevraFCM=
mDhl8oZ05ANv1APOpt_Lrx737wFd8bDT7v_fWT06sZEjWnnFHBFRsplXRgwyip8otkS3A2MKYsZ=
8FOQk4TOJgg3ATdVz7U5ipa_3z_R4pOGV0uMa19_HzYHbbPoGcy_d5bingaSNZtEK64eFH7ADAr=
JCidZjAWOyu2CMFpxyXpFa_zGGVv9zVJdw65q9K_6R9QSYNe] pointed out that a lot of=
 the work a normal startup would have to do gets handled by the blockchain =
itself, by other protocols, and by the community:=C2=A0
The blockchain handles the rails - security, how the transactions settle, m=
ovement of money, etc=E2=80=A6 that removes the scaling headache for a youn=
g company.=C2=A0
Projects like Metamask [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAQRE8zLC=
1-7c-CRTa5htWYjgeNDRa0E_n2IeNFJARqSqXqegsyrblc7siVxd8183WQS_RTN2KmIs5KZY7Bq=
V6PBuwkgrNBjTCKWOevQrRj3ByXk8Rx-i0uyDGnt0NKDeLpLIzSUHP0YLwnhDABfgGEPhgcQd-5=
eIZIaSFH31SunEhs7sl81If5eOjPdnZi3LG-upjbJKLTUitpda-MlCA71RmQ_TKBmoLHoFSPWgU=
cLAwDeRooPKzcV93V01fG5dUteRfFpcw-l5jWJr-euNP2Flqbub37mSJfMyX0G4W7KN-83tXnlR=
KVxjHMyI2SmqzVsoECeRdrJAy077amaMkhN1f6D_0FlXiAmw] remove the need for accou=
nt creation - just connect your Metamask and you=E2=80=99re in, along with =
your money.=C2=A0
You don=E2=80=99t need customer service because people understand that it=
=E2=80=99s self-custody, and if you send your crypto to the wrong place, th=
at=E2=80=99s on you. There=E2=80=99s literally nothing a customer service t=
eam could do to fix that anyway.
Early users are also investors and community members, and do much of your m=
arketing for you.=C2=A0
Other projects built on the same protocol become =E2=80=9Clegos=E2=80=9D th=
at you can snap into place to add new functionality to your product.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
Simplifying it, he said, =E2=80=9CYou focus on your core value proposition,=
 and the Ethereum chain takes care of everything else.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
As a Web3 startup, you have scale from day 1, because you borrow the blockc=
hain=E2=80=99s scale. As a result, Web3 companies can be like API-first com=
panies [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhSAMQL_mstPw9LFgMZv5DQNSlQ=
yCARzj30_nmswkFNI2zaFnNhXWlG99pFLJ7zXV-wAd4SoBaoVMzgJ58k6zjg9CyZE4LR0b1EB8m=
ZYMsBsfdM0nkOO0wc-m-hTfE5RyRTa9uAG4W_hAFbhFzqJXox1FZy2zPSYP15zOQ5xBwzfkO0Ug=
QW-1HuUlPl78E891XW1M1abs49rOCUsHhjl8aUwITd2guczduHRF4jWnnFHJOyYoVbRlrVC0m0f=
FRmeNY6wznDnTS9X3YKEH95J0X3lbTluqmb-QsJOs_4jY_trMDuHdwF0nfPcz-npPEI0N4B4N9b=
H5FjOtECGjZTeZig7ZKCWnqFHRZ230JBSW8ZsEyS7hVPyH_gDClov6] on steroids. They c=
an focus on what they do best and outsource everything else to the chain, a=
nd to other protocols. Scalability and composability.=C2=A0
That should be terrifying to the incumbents. Built-in scalability, composab=
ility among protocols, and programmable money are a formula that might allo=
w Web3 projects to low-end disrupt the seemingly undisruptable.
